    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What do Germany's official crime statistics show about non-German nationals?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Germany's Federal Criminal Police (BKA) Polizeiliche Kriminalstatistik (PKS) 2023 shows a suspect rate of 5.36% for non-German nationals vs. 1.46% for German nationals — a ratio of approximately 3.7×. This is a per-capita rate (not absolute counts). The gap is substantially explained by differences in age structure (non-German nationals have a higher share of young men), urban concentration, and socioeconomic status. BKA classifies by nationality, not by immigrant background, so second-generation immigrants with German citizenship are counted in the German national category."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does Germany's immigration crime data compare to Sweden and Denmark?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Germany (BKA PKS 2023): 3.7× ratio by nationality. Sweden (BRÅ 2021): ~2.5× by immigrant background (born abroad or both parents born abroad). Denmark (DST): 2.6× age-adjusted by immigrant/descendant category. Direct comparison is not valid because the population categories differ: Germany uses nationality, while Sweden and Denmark use immigrant background — which includes naturalised citizens that Germany counts in the 'German' category."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>
</main>
